<body>

<h1>@HI{{tameni}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @FORMATION{{@Vru{{}}(<em>volitional</em>) @HI{{@EM{{tameni}}}}, <em>volitional expression</em>}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@N{{}}@HI{{no}}@HI{{@EM{{tameni}}}}}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@Ai{{}}@HI{{@EM{{tameni}}}}}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@Ana{{}}@HI{{@EM{{tameni}}}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="purpose">This</a> sentence pattern indicates a purpose if the main clause is a volitional expression.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KJ{{oneself}}@KJ{{part}}@HI{{no}}@KJ{{store}}@HI{{wo}}@KJ{{hold}}@HI{{tsu}}@HI{{@EM{{tameni}}}},
      @KJ{{savings}}@KJ{{gold}}@HI{{shiteimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I am saving money in order to have my own shop.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="reason">If</a> the main clause is non-volitional, then @HI{{@EM{{tameni}}}} is interpreted to mean a reason or cause.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{attend^matter}}no@EM{{tameni}}@KJ{{what}}mohokano@KJ{{matter}}ga@KJ{{exit^come}}nai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Because of the job I cannot do anything else.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="sono">The</a> reason or cause can be stated in the first sentence and then referenced with @HI{{sono}} in the immediately following sentence.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{detain^study}}:ryuugaku}}surutsumorida.@EM{{sonotameni}},@KT{{baito}}shiteo@FG{{@KJ{{gold}}:kane}}wotameteiru.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I am planning to study abroad. That's why I am saving money by working part-time.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="benefit">The</a> pattern @N{{}}@HI{{no@EM{{tameni}}}} can also indicate "for the benefit of @N{{}}".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KJ{{house}}@KJ{{tribe}}@HI{{no}}@HI{{@EM{{tameni}}}},@HI{{uchi wo}}@KJ{{build}}@HI{{temasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I will build a house for my family.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="predicate">It</a> is possible to state the result first and the cause or reason as a predicate.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{}}:kuukou}}ga@FG{{@KJ{{make}}:tsuka}}enakunattanoha,@FG{{@KJ{{large^snow}}:ooyuki}}ga@FG{{@KJ{{descend}}:fu}}tta@EM{{tame}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The reason that the airport became unusable was that a lot of snow fell.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
The similar expression <a href="grammar-you-ni.html">@HI{{youni}}</a>
 is used in clauses with verbs that do not contain volition,
whereas @HI{{@EM{{tameni}}}} is used with verbs that do. Note that if the verb involved
is @HI{{naru}}, then whether or not volition is invovled depends on the sentence.
</p>

